# Canvas/WebGL Technology Research

> **Research Date:** January 2026
> **Project Context:** MMS V1.0 - Metro Maintenance Planning System
> **Current Implementation:** React Three Fiber 8.x + drei 9.x + InstancedMesh

---

## Executive Summary

This document provides comprehensive research on canvas/WebGL technologies for the MMS visualization system. The current implementation uses React Three Fiber (R3F) with InstancedMesh for rendering 60k+ tasks at 60fps. This research validates the technology choices and provides best practices for V1.0 optimization.

**Key Findings:**
1. **R3F 8.x + React 18** is the correct pairing (R3F 9 requires React 19)
2. **InstancedMesh** is appropriate for 60k objects; use BVH for advanced culling
3. **deck.gl** could be an alternative but migration complexity outweighs benefits
4. **RBush** spatial indexing is optimal for viewport culling
5. **GC avoidance** through object pooling and TypedArrays is critical for 60fps

---

## 1. React Three Fiber Status

### Current Version Pairing (Critical)

| React Version | R3F Version | drei Version | Status |
|---------------|-------------|--------------|--------|
| **React 18** | **@react-three/fiber@8.x** | **@react-three/drei@9.x** | **Current MMS** |
| React 19 | @react-three/fiber@9.x | @react-three/drei@10.x | Future option |

**Source:** [React Three Fiber npm](https://www.npmjs.com/package/@react-three/fiber)

### React 18 Compatibility Confirmed

- R3F 8.x pairs with React 18 (as documented)
- BlueprintJS 6 requires React 18, making this pairing mandatory for MMS
- StrictMode inheritance works correctly in R3F 8.x

### Breaking Changes in R3F v9 (NOT applicable to current MMS)

1. **StrictMode now inherited** from parent renderer (react-dom)
2. **TypeScript changes:** `Props` renamed to `CanvasProps`
3. **JSX types:** Access via `ThreeElements['mesh']` instead of `MeshProps`
4. **Node helpers removed:** Use unified `ThreeElement<T>` type
5. **Async GL prop:** Canvas `gl` callback receives constructor params

**Source:** [R3F v9 Migration Guide](https://r3f.docs.pmnd.rs/tutorials/v9-migration-guide)

### React 18 Performance Features

React 18 introduces concurrent scheduling via `startTransition` and `useTransition`:
- Virtualizes component graph for prioritization
- Can defer expensive operations
- Helps maintain stable framerate under load

**Recommendation:** Use `startTransition` for heavy state updates that don't need immediate UI response.

---

## 2. InstancedMesh Patterns

### Core Benefits

InstancedMesh reduces draw calls from N (one per object) to 1, significantly improving WebGL performance.

**Performance envelope:**
- **Optimal:** 1,000 - 100,000 instances
- **MMS target:** ~60,000 tasks
- **Desktop performance:** Excellent
- **Mobile caveat:** May actually be slower than naive rendering on low-end devices (Quest 2 example: 85fps naive vs 55fps instanced at 2600 instances)

**Source:** [Three.js Forum - When is InstancedMesh worth it](https://discourse.threejs.org/t/when-is-instancedmesh-worth-it-in-three/62044)

### Creation and Updates

```typescript
// Create InstancedMesh
const mesh = new THREE.InstancedMesh(geometry, material, count);

// Update transform for instance i
const matrix = new THREE.Matrix4();
matrix.compose(position, quaternion, scale);
mesh.setMatrixAt(i, matrix);
mesh.instanceMatrix.needsUpdate = true; // CRITICAL: Mark for GPU update

// Update color for instance i
mesh.setColorAt(i, color);
mesh.instanceColor!.needsUpdate = true; // CRITICAL
```

**Source:** [Three.js InstancedMesh Docs](https://threejs.org/docs/pages/InstancedMesh.html)

### Attribute Buffers Best Practices

1. **Always set `needsUpdate = true`** after modifying `instanceMatrix` or `instanceColor`
2. **Compute bounding box manually** - not auto-calculated, call after transforms
3. **Use `count` property** to hide instances dynamically (set lower than allocated)
4. **Pre-allocate** to maximum needed count to avoid recreating mesh

### Color Management

```typescript
// Set per-instance colors
const color = new THREE.Color();
for (let i = 0; i < count; i++) {
  color.setHex(getColorForInstance(i));
  mesh.setColorAt(i, color);
}
mesh.instanceColor!.needsUpdate = true;
```

### Performance Limits and Optimization

| Technique | Benefit | When to Use |
|-----------|---------|-------------|
| **LOD with multiple InstancedMesh** | ~2x FPS improvement | Complex geometries |
| **Per-instance frustum culling** | Skip off-screen instances | Scattered world-space data |
| **BVH spatial index** | Fast culling + raycasting | Mostly static instances |
| **Custom sorting for transparency** | Correct render order | Transparent materials |

**Source:** [VR Me Up - InstancedMesh Performance Optimizations](https://vrmeup.com/devlog/devlog_10_threejs_instancedmesh_performance_optimizations.html)

### Enhanced Libraries

**@three.ez/instanced-mesh** (InstancedMesh2):
- Dynamic instance addition
- Object3D-like instances with transforms
- Built-in per-instance frustum culling
- BVH support for raycasting

**Recommendation:** Consider for future if frustum culling becomes a bottleneck.

**Source:** [npm - @three.ez/instanced-mesh](https://www.npmjs.com/package/@three.ez/instanced-mesh)

### Resource Cleanup

```typescript
// CRITICAL: Dispose on unmount to free GPU memory
useEffect(() => {
  return () => {
    mesh.dispose();
    geometry.dispose();
    material.dispose();
  };
}, []);
```

---

## 3. deck.gl Comparison

### deck.gl Overview

deck.gl is a WebGL2/WebGPU visualization framework optimized for large-scale data visualization.

**Performance envelope:**
- ~1M data items at 60 FPS on 2015 MacBook Pro
- Performance degrades significantly approaching 10M items
- Browser memory limits practical usage to 10M-100M without chunking

**Source:** [deck.gl Performance Optimization](https://deck.gl/docs/developer-guide/performance)

### OrthographicView for 2D

OrthographicView is designed for non-geospatial 2D visualization:

```javascript
import { OrthographicView } from '@deck.gl/core';

const view = new OrthographicView({
  controller: true,
  flipY: true // top-left coordinates
});

// View state
const viewState = {
  target: [0, 0, 0],
  zoom: 1,
  minZoom: -2,
  maxZoom: 10
};
```

**Source:** [deck.gl OrthographicView](https://deck.gl/docs/api-reference/core/orthographic-view)

### Pros vs R3F for MMS

| Aspect | deck.gl | React Three Fiber |
|--------|---------|-------------------|
| **2D Timeline** | Designed for this | Requires workarounds |
| **Data binding** | Excellent (layer props) | Manual attribute updates |
| **64-bit projection** | Built-in | Manual |
| **Picking** | Built-in (16M items/layer) | Manual raycasting |
| **React integration** | Fair (@deck.gl/react) | Excellent (native renderer) |
| **3D capabilities** | Limited | Excellent |
| **Learning curve** | Moderate | Lower (Three.js knowledge) |
| **LOD transitions** | Layer visibility | Manual implementation |

### Cons vs R3F for MMS

1. **Migration cost:** Existing R3F implementation is working
2. **Less flexible:** deck.gl layers have fixed capabilities
3. **Shader customization:** Harder than Three.js ShaderMaterial
4. **Community size:** Smaller than Three.js ecosystem

### deck.gl Layer Performance Tips

```javascript
// Use typed arrays for performance
const data = {
  length: 60000,
  attributes: {
    getPosition: new Float32Array(/* ... */),
    getColor: new Uint8Array(/* ... */)
  }
};

// Use visibility instead of removing layers
layer.visible = false; // Preserves GPU resources

// Use updateTriggers for selective updates
updateTriggers: {
  getColor: colorVersion // Only update color when version changes
}
```

**Source:** [deck.gl Performance](https://deck.gl/docs/developer-guide/performance)

### Recommendation: Stay with R3F

**Rationale:**
1. Current R3F implementation is functional and performant
2. Migration to deck.gl would require significant rewrite
3. R3F provides more flexibility for custom visualizations
4. Three.js ecosystem has better community support
5. deck.gl advantages (data binding, picking) can be replicated in R3F

---

## 4. Spatial Indexing with RBush

### RBush Overview

RBush is a high-performance 2D spatial index based on an optimized R-tree with bulk-loading support.

**Performance characteristics:**
- Bulk loading: 2-3x faster than sequential insertion
- Query performance: ~30x faster than linear scan
- Post-bulk-load queries: 20-30% better than individual insertions

**Source:** [RBush GitHub](https://github.com/mourner/rbush)

### Current Version

- **Version:** 4.0.1 (ES module only, no CommonJS)
- **Data format:** `{ minX, minY, maxX, maxY }` by default

### API Reference

```typescript
import RBush from 'rbush';

// Create tree (default nodeSize: 9)
const tree = new RBush();

// Bulk load (recommended for initial data)
tree.load(items); // 2-3x faster than sequential insert

// Insert single item
tree.insert({ minX: 0, maxX: 10, minY: 0, maxY: 10, data: taskId });

// Search (returns items intersecting bbox)
const visible = tree.search({
  minX: viewportLeft,
  maxX: viewportRight,
  minY: viewportTop,
  maxY: viewportBottom
});

// Fast collision check (boolean)
const hasOverlap = tree.collides(bbox);

// Remove item
tree.remove(item);

// Serialization
const json = tree.toJSON();
tree.fromJSON(json);
```

### Bulk Loading Pattern (MMS Implementation)

```typescript
// Convert tasks to spatial index format
const spatialItems = tasks.map(task => ({
  minX: task.startDay * PX_PER_DAY,
  maxX: (task.startDay + task.duration) * PX_PER_DAY,
  minY: -task.trainIndex * PX_PER_TRAIN - PX_PER_TRAIN,
  maxY: -task.trainIndex * PX_PER_TRAIN,
  task // Store reference to original task
}));

// Bulk load (2-3x faster + 20-30% better query performance)
const tree = new RBush();
tree.load(spatialItems);

// Query visible tasks
function getVisibleTasks(viewportBounds) {
  return tree.search({
    minX: viewportBounds.minX - OVERSCAN,
    maxX: viewportBounds.maxX + OVERSCAN,
    minY: viewportBounds.minY - OVERSCAN,
    maxY: viewportBounds.maxY + OVERSCAN
  }).map(item => item.task);
}
```

### Query Optimization

1. **Use overscan margin:** Query slightly larger area to avoid pop-in
2. **Avoid frequent re-indexing:** RBush is optimized for mostly-static data
3. **Consider kdbush for static points:** 5-8x faster for point-only queries

**Alternative for static data:** [kdbush](https://github.com/mourner/kdbush) - 5-8x faster for point indexing

### Integration with React

```typescript
// useSpatialIndex hook (existing MMS pattern)
function useSpatialIndex(tasks: TaskRender[]): ISpatialIndex {
  return useMemo(() => {
    const tree = new RBush();
    tree.load(tasks.map(taskToSpatialItem));
    return {
      search: (bounds) => tree.search(bounds).map(i => i.task),
      collides: (bounds) => tree.collides(bounds)
    };
  }, [tasks]); // Rebuild only when tasks change
}
```

---

## 5. Performance Optimization

### GC Avoidance (Critical for 60fps)

The main performance bottleneck in JavaScript WebGL applications is **Garbage Collection**, not rendering.

**Why GC is problematic:**
- GC timing is unpredictable
- Can cause frame drops and stuttering
- No direct control over when it runs

**Source:** [Wonderland Engine - WebGL Performance](https://wonderlandengine.com/about/webgl-performance/)

### Object Pooling Pattern

```typescript
// Object pool for reusing temporary objects
class ObjectPool<T> {
  private pool: T[] = [];
  private factory: () => T;

  constructor(factory: () => T, initialSize: number = 10) {
    this.factory = factory;
    for (let i = 0; i < initialSize; i++) {
      this.pool.push(factory());
    }
  }

  acquire(): T {
    return this.pool.pop() || this.factory();
  }

  release(obj: T): void {
    this.pool.push(obj);
  }
}

// Usage for Three.js vectors/matrices
const vector3Pool = new ObjectPool(() => new THREE.Vector3(), 50);
const matrix4Pool = new ObjectPool(() => new THREE.Matrix4(), 50);

// In animation loop
function update() {
  const temp = vector3Pool.acquire();
  temp.set(x, y, z);
  // ... use temp ...
  vector3Pool.release(temp);
}
```

### TypedArrays and Memory

```typescript
// Use TypedArrays for large data sets
const positions = new Float32Array(count * 3);
const colors = new Uint8Array(count * 4);

// Benefits:
// - Contiguous memory allocation
// - No GC for individual elements
// - Direct GPU upload
// - Cache-friendly iteration
```

**Source:** [MDN - WebGL Best Practices](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/WebGL_API/WebGL_best_practices)

### useFrame Best Practices (R3F)

```typescript
// BAD: Creates garbage every frame
useFrame(() => {
  ref.current.position.lerp(new THREE.Vector3(x, y, z), 0.1);
});

// GOOD: Reuse objects
const targetRef = useRef(new THREE.Vector3());
useFrame((state, delta) => {
  targetRef.current.set(x, y, z);
  ref.current.position.lerp(targetRef.current, delta * 5);
});
```

**Source:** [R3F Performance Pitfalls](https://r3f.docs.pmnd.rs/advanced/pitfalls)

### Frame Budget Analysis

**Target:** 60fps = 16.67ms per frame

| Operation | Budget | Priority |
|-----------|--------|----------|
| Render (GPU) | ~8ms | Critical |
| JavaScript | ~5ms | Critical |
| Layout/Paint | ~2ms | Low |
| GC | 0ms target | Eliminate |

### Structure of Arrays (SoA) Pattern

**AoS (Array of Structs):** Traditional object-oriented pattern
```typescript
// Bad for performance with large datasets
const tasks = [
  { x: 0, y: 0, width: 10, color: 'blue' },
  { x: 10, y: 0, width: 5, color: 'red' }
];
```

**SoA (Struct of Arrays):** Cache-friendly pattern
```typescript
// Good for batch processing
const taskData = {
  x: new Float32Array([0, 10, ...]),
  y: new Float32Array([0, 0, ...]),
  width: new Float32Array([10, 5, ...]),
  color: new Uint8Array([0, 1, ...]) // Color index
};
```

**Performance impact:** 10-100x improvement for batch operations due to:
- Better CPU cache utilization
- SIMD vectorization opportunities
- GPU memory coalescing

**Source:** [SoA vs AoS Performance](https://lobste.rs/s/gs5ujg/why_object_arrays_soa_pattern_beat)

### WebGL Draw Call Optimization

**Batching rules:**
- Target < 1000 draw calls
- Use instancing for repeated geometry
- Use texture atlases for multiple textures
- Use `WEBGL_multi_draw` extension when available

**Source:** [MDN - WebGL Best Practices](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/WebGL_API/WebGL_best_practices)

---

## 6. Semantic Zoom Implementation

### Definition

Semantic zoom changes the **meaning and representation** of visualized data at different zoom levels, not just the geometric detail (which is Level of Detail/LOD).

**Source:** [InfoVis Wiki - Semantic Zoom](https://infovis-wiki.net/wiki/Semantic_Zoom)

### MMS LOD Thresholds (Current Implementation)

| LOD Level | Zoom Range | Visualization | Data Resolution |
|-----------|------------|---------------|-----------------|
| **MACRO** | < 0.5x | Heatmap (aggregated) | 10-20 year overview |
| **MESO** | 0.5x - 2.0x | Task blocks (DNA pattern) | 2-5 year detail |
| **MICRO** | > 2.0x | Detailed cards + labels | 4-8 week focus |

### Crossfade Implementation (Current MMS)

```typescript
// Calculate opacity for smooth transitions
function calculateLayerOpacities(zoom: number): { macro: number; meso: number; micro: number } {
  const BLEND_ZONE_SIZE = 0.15;

  const macroEnd = 0.5 - BLEND_ZONE_SIZE;   // 0.35
  const mesoStart = 0.5 + BLEND_ZONE_SIZE;  // 0.65
  const mesoEnd = 2.0 - BLEND_ZONE_SIZE;    // 1.85
  const microStart = 2.0 + BLEND_ZONE_SIZE; // 2.15

  // Linear interpolation in blend zones
  // Both layers render during transition with interpolated opacity
}
```

### Three.js LOD Limitations

Three.js built-in `THREE.LOD` does **abrupt switches**, not crossfade:
- Based on camera distance, not zoom level
- No native opacity transition
- Requires custom implementation for smooth crossfade

**Source:** [Three.js LOD Docs](https://threejs.org/docs/pages/LOD.html)

### Crossfade with Transparent Materials

**Challenges:**
1. Transparent objects require depth sorting
2. Overlapping transparent objects can cause artifacts
3. Performance cost of rendering two layers

**Solutions:**
```typescript
// Set transparency properties
material.transparent = true;
material.opacity = 0.5;
material.depthWrite = false; // Important for proper blending
```

**For complex scenes:** Consider rendering to separate render targets and compositing.

**Source:** [Three.js Forum - Cross fade transparent objects](https://discourse.threejs.org/t/cross-fade-with-a-third-scene-or-how-to-cross-fade-transparent-objects-in-a-complex-scene/24849)

### Layer Switching Pattern

```tsx
// Render only visible layers (current MMS pattern)
function LODLayers({ zoom, tasks }) {
  const opacities = useMemo(() => calculateLayerOpacities(zoom), [zoom]);

  return (
    <group>
      {opacities.macro > 0 && <MacroLayer opacity={opacities.macro} ... />}
      {opacities.meso > 0 && <MesoLayer opacity={opacities.meso} ... />}
      {opacities.micro > 0 && <MicroLayer opacity={opacities.micro} ... />}
    </group>
  );
}
```

### Academic References

- **Ken Perlin & David Fox:** "Pad: an alternative approach to the computer interface" (SIGGRAPH '93)
- **Ben Shneiderman:** "The Eyes Have It: A Task by Data Type Taxonomy for Information Visualizations" (1996)
- **Wiens, Lohmann, Auer:** "Semantic Zooming for Ontology Graph Visualizations" (K-CAP 2017)

**Source:** [ACM - Semantic Zooming for Ontology Graph Visualizations](https://dl.acm.org/doi/10.1145/3148011.3148015)

